<sn><md>### Philosophy

:::.row
:::.col-7 .col-md-9
The earliest known Chinese philosopher was `Laozi`. His philosophy became known as `Taoism (Daoism)`.
:::
:::.col-5 .col-md-3
![img](https://miro.medium.com/1*8-Xd1YP70qiJWddAQtzAVA.jpeg)
:::
:::

:::.row
:::.col-7 .col-md-3
![img](https://w7.pngwing.com/pngs/396/123/png-transparent-confucius-thumbnail.png)
:::
:::.col-5 .col-md-9
The most ++influential++ philosopher in Chinese history was `Confucius`. His teachings formed the basis of `Confucianism`, which profoundly shaped Chinese society, culture, and government.
:::
:::


:::.row
:::.col-7 .col-md-9
The principal follower and interpreter of Confucius was `Mencius`, who further developed Confucian thought.
:::
:::.col-5 .col-md-3
![img](https://ericgerlach.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/mencius.jpg)
:::
:::


:::.row
:::.col-7 .col-md-3
![img](https://framerusercontent.com/images/XlbP969rz8XeW271fnQn8uDgjG0.png)
:::
:::.col-5 .col-md-9
`Sun Tzu` was an ancient Chinese ++military commander++, strategist, and philosopher. He is traditionally regarded as the author of the famous military treatise `The Art of War`, one of the most influential books on warfare and strategy ever written.
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### The Great Wall of China

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-8
The `Great Wall of China` is the ++largest man-made structure++ in the world and is located along `China's northern frontier`. During the `Ming Dynasty`, the measured length of the wall, including trenches and natural barriers, was approximately `8,850 km (5,500 miles)`. The wall itself extends for about `6,269 km (3,889 miles)`.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-4
![Image](https://images.openai.com/static-rsc-4/lJFX9yf0Q5Q7zTDHB_mWdjdh58b_EtmYvQsnFk0WBIyFcgijNgivEL7ELcilWQ0XwPBPGCzRAiYIPcG4caMfWX4nGUyjqPGY2fAZ0ekag5UBc6zRY06LRa4bSAJU2PXwSI1DEpDv4V6qcuyYCndbAXpSJuvdN8C7EWfrDeZr1_OumNWKypzTeW2fR0dGGQRN?purpose=fullsize)
:::
:::


**Periods of Construction**

The Great Wall was built and expanded during several historical periods:

| Period / Dynasty      | Time Period    |
| --------------------- | -------------- |
| Warring States Period | 770–221 BCE    |
| Qin Dynasty           | 221–207 BCE    |
| Han Dynasty           | 206 BCE–220 CE |
| Ming Dynasty          | 1368–1644 CE   |
| Qing Dynasty          | 1644–1911 CE   |
